Infrastructure Investment & Jobs Act Funding Allocation

Is the allocation equitable based on the population of each of the States and Territories, or is bias apparent?

Does the allocation favor the political interests of the Biden administration? Notes:

You will need to source data on the current (estimated) population of each of the States and Territories (accuracy is more important than precision) and on the official election results of the 2020 Presidential election.

grouped_voting <- prez_voting_df |> group_by(state,party_simplified) |> summarise(sum_perc =sum(percent_vote)) |> summarise(top_party=max(sum_perc))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'state'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
top_party_df <- inner_join(prez_voting_df,grouped_voting,by=c("state"='state','percent_vote'='top_party'))
head(top_party_df)

fund_pop_df <- left_join(state_funding_df,american_pop_df,by=c("geographic_area"="geographic_area"))
dim(fund_pop_df)
## [1] 57  3
head(fund_pop_df)
## # A tibble: 6 × 3
##   geographic_area Dollars_Allocated population_2020
##   <chr>                       <dbl>           <dbl>
## 1 ALABAMA                    3              5024356
## 2 ALASKA                     3.7             733378
## 3 AMERICAN SAMOA             0.0686           49710
## 4 ARIZONA                    3.5            7151507
## 5 ARKANSAS                   2.8            3011555
## 6 CALIFORNIA                18.4           39538245
perc_totals <- fund_pop_df |>
summarise(perc_allocations=Dollars_Allocated/sum(Dollars_Allocated),perc_population=population_2020/sum(population_2020))

full_df <- cbind(fund_pop_df,perc_totals)
full_df <- full_df |> mutate(perc_diff=perc_allocations-perc_population,dollar_per_resident=10^9*Dollars_Allocated/population_2020) 
dim(full_df)
## [1] 57  7

full_votes_df <- left_join(full_df,top_party_df,by=c('geographic_area'='state'))
ggplot(full_df,aes(geographic_area,perc_diff,fill=population_2020))+
    geom_bar(stat='identity',position='dodge') +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90,size=7)) +
    labs(title="Differential between funding allocated to each state/territory and the respective 2020 population",
    x='US State/Territory',y='Percentage Differential',subtitle='Infrastructure Investment & Jobs Act funding')

politic_compare <- ggplot(full_votes_df,aes(reorder(geographic_area,-perc_diff),perc_diff,fill=party_simplified))+
    geom_bar(stat='identity',position='dodge') +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90,size=8)) +
    labs(title="Differential between funding allocated to each US state/territory and the respective 2020 population",
    x='',y='Percentage Differential',subtitle='Infrastructure Investment & Jobs Act funding',fill='Nominated 2020 Party') +
    scale_fill_manual(values=c('blue', 'red', 'grey')) 
 politic_compare   + theme(legend.position = 'bottom')

full_votes_df$pop_scaled <- scale(full_votes_df$population_2020)
full_votes_df$dollars_scaled <- scale(full_votes_df$Dollars_Allocated)
ggplot(full_votes_df,aes(x=dollars_scaled,y=pop_scaled),fill=party_simplified,size=percent_vote) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_jitter() +
    geom_text(aes(label=state_po),color='black',size=2.8,vjust=1)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_text).

pop_per_person_bar <- ggplot(full_votes_df,aes(x=reorder(geographic_area,population_2020),y=dollar_per_resident,fill=party_simplified)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    labs(title="Funding driven not by population or current president's political party",
    x='US State/Territory',y='Dollars Per Person',subtitle='Sorted by population as of 2020 census descending',fill='Nominated 2020 Party') +
    coord_flip() +
    scale_fill_manual(values=c('blue', 'red', 'grey')) 
 pop_per_person_bar   + theme(legend.position = 'bottom')

base_graph <- full_df %>% select(c(geographic_area,perc_allocations,perc_population,population_2020)) %>% pivot_longer(cols=c('perc_allocations','perc_population'),names_to='measure_names',values_to='measure_values') %>% 
    group_by(geographic_area,measure_names,population_2020) %>% ggplot(aes(x=reorder(geographic_area,population_2020),y=measure_values,fill=measure_names)) + 
    geom_bar(stat='identity',position='dodge') + 
    coord_flip()
    base_graph + theme(axis.text = element_text(vjust=0.7,size = 5)) +
    labs(title='Population size does not determine IIJA funding?',y='Percentages',x='US States/Territories',fill='Measures') +
    scale_fill_manual(labels=c('Percentage of All Allocated Funds','Percentage of Total US 2020 Population') ,values=c('blue', 'orange'))
